Feature: a launched bc-base BC carries a self-contained fabro loop def that "fabro validate" accepts, with the native fabro vault holding only placeholders

  SLICE 2 of the fabro launch path (epic lead-kqgp, under lead-6k1r; S2 work_id
  lead-ky63, target shopsystem-bc-launcher). S1 (scenario 73,
  @scenario_hash:a3512aedb8763150) baked the fabro SUBSTRATE — the fabro binary
  v0.254.0 and the anthropic-oauth-shim — into bc-base:latest. Substrate alone
  orchestrates nothing: fabro needs a DEF to run. This scenario pins the next
  hard prerequisite: after "bc-container launch <bc>", the launched container
  carries a self-contained, valid fabro def — the bc-shop Implementer->Reviewer
  loop graph — that "fabro validate" accepts, and whose native fabro vault
  carries only "__PLACEHOLDER__" values.

  SOURCE-AGNOSTIC (decomposition 06b). This pins only that "a valid def is
  PRESENT" in the launched container after launch. It deliberately does NOT pin
  HOW the def got there — whether the def content is inlined into the launcher
  as a materialized asset (S2) or later poured from shop-templates (S7/S8). S7/S8
  swap the def's source without changing this launcher behavior; the assertions
  below survive that swap unchanged.

  WHAT "VALID + SELF-CONTAINED" MEANS HERE.
    - VALID: "fabro validate" over the def exits zero and reports zero
      diagnostics. Per the ADR-051 DOT loop-graph contract, the graph is the
      bc-shop Implementer->Reviewer loop in which the Reviewer is the SOLE gated
      work_done emitter and every fallible node fails CLOSED (an explicit
      unconditional failsafe edge to a halt/emit_blk sink; a FAILED node never
      advances to the SUCCEEDED terminal).
    - SELF-CONTAINED: the def carries not only the graph file but every node
      body the graph references, so the loop is runnable from the def alone with
      nothing fetched at run time. ("fabro validate" is permissive and binds the
      graph file structurally; self-containment is the stronger property this
      scenario also asserts, because that is what makes the def genuinely
      runnable in-container.)

  NATIVE-VAULT INVARIANT (ADR-049). The def's native fabro vault holds only
  "__PLACEHOLDER__" for its provider-key / token slots — NO real credential. Real
  credentials ride the agent-vault surface (the shim + HTTPS_PROXY path baked in
  S1), never the fabro vault. This scenario pins the STATIC placeholder invariant
  over the def-as-shipped; the live credential round-trip is the distinct S3
  behavior and is not asserted here.

  LAUNCH PARITY (ADR-050). This is a property of the ALREADY-launched container;
  it changes nothing about the launch interface itself (tmux default unchanged,
  shop-msg mailbox preserved). It is the runtime observable — parallel to
  scenario 73 (fabro/shim present) and scenario 64
  (@scenario_hash:04f2c7501273705c, gh + agent-vault on PATH) — not a build-time
  Dockerfile-content pin. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher / bc-base, owned per
  ADR-021.)

  @scenario_hash:2dfefe2ba81e418d
  Scenario: a launched bc-base BC has a self-contained valid fabro loop def that "fabro validate" accepts with the native fabro vault holding only placeholders
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And bc-container launch is run with BC name "shopsystem-messaging"
    And the container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running on the pinned bc-base image
    When "fabro validate" is executed against the fabro def present in that running container
    Then it exits zero and reports zero diagnostics
    And the def is a self-contained bc-shop Implementer->Reviewer loop graph per ADR-051: the graph file is present, every node body the graph references is present in the def alongside it so the loop is runnable from the def alone, the Reviewer node is the sole node that can emit a gated work_done on the success path, and every fallible node carries an explicit unconditional failsafe edge to a halt or blocked-emit sink so a failed node never advances to the SUCCEEDED terminal
    And the def's native fabro vault holds only the value "__PLACEHOLDER__" for each of its provider-key and token slots, with no real credential present in the def (ADR-049), so that any real credential the loop uses is sourced from the agent-vault surface baked in S1 and never from the fabro vault
